<div id="PJA12d186" class="doc letter">

<h2>From C. W. F. Dumas</h2>

<div class="docbody" xml:lang="fra">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		  <td class="salutationLeft">Monsieur</td>
		  <td class="salutationRight">La haie 23e. Fevr. 1782</td>
		</tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>La maison que Votre Excellence ma ordonn dacheter Vous appartient depuis hier au Soir, que nous en avons pass le Contrat de vente par-devant notaires de la main  la main, pour quatorze mille cinquante deux et demi florins, je dis 14052.10s argent courant, et franc de tous fraix, dHollande, de votre part, moyennant quoi le Vendeur est tenu de vous livrer au premier de May prochain la maison  son tour, telle que vous lavez vue, franche de toutes dettes et<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="ADMS-06-12-02-pb-0262">[262]</span> autres charges.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA12d187n1" id="PJA12d187n1-ptr">1</a> Pour condition, jai d promettre dans le Contrat de payer  compte, avant le 1er. de Mars prochain, la somme de 8000, (cest pour acquitter lhypotheque pour la quelle la maison est hypothque) et les 6052.10 restants avant le premier de May prochain, lorsque le transport se fera en forme. Pour cet effet, jai tir aujourdhui  mon ordre, et endoss  celui de Mrs. Moliere fils &amp; Ce., une Lettre de change de 10,000 argt. court. dHollande, contre laquelle il ma donn deux reus payables au porteur, lun, de 8000, que je remettrai au Notaire, lautre de 2000, dont je disposerai chez Mrs. Moliere moi-mme,  mesure que jaurai besoin de deniers comptants pour acquitter les fraix du pays et autres pour lachat, &amp;c. et aprs, vous tenir compte, Monsieur, du solde. Quant aux 6052.10 restants, je les tirerai pareillement sur vous, pour pouvoir les payer avant le 1er. May, lorsque le transport se fera. Mon Notaire, qui est aussi celui de lHotel de France, me dlivrera Lundi prochain une Copie du Contrat pass hier, laquelle jespere de vous porter moi-mme, ds que jaurai arrang le payement de lachat et des fraix. Je crois devoir vous avertir, Monsieur, de la condition dusage constant, enonce aussi dans le contrat, que la maison est ds la signature dhier aux prils et risques de lacheteur, afin que, pour votre tranquillit, vous puissiez la faire assurer, si vous le jugez  propos.</p>
<p>Au reste, jai marchand tout ce qui toit possible, jusquau dernier instant, et le Vendeur a eu justement le temps encore de faire arrter la vente publique. Par-l je vous ai pargn, Monsieur, 700 de fraix de plus au moins, outre ceux dun repas. On en avoit offert 13000 mardi pass; et jai eu soin de massurer depuis, que je ne laurois pas eue  moins de 14000,  la dite Vente publique. Je me flatte donc que ma conduite  tous gards mritera votre approbation, et que vous voudrez bien Monsieur, mapprendre, par un mot de rponse, que vous tes content de moi, et recevoir mon compliment sur cette acquisition, et mes voeux pour que vous en jouissiez avec sant et toutes sortes de satisfactions, avec un plaisir gal  la sincrit et labondance du coeur qui vous les prsente.</p>
<p>Le moment aprs la signature du Contrat, je courus  lhtel de France (quoiquil y et Bal), prier le Secretaire de M. le Duc de la Vauguyon, den informer Son Excellence et lon vient de me dire, que ce matin le Coureur de M. le Duc de Brunswick est all  notre Htel, sinformer de laffaire auprs de la Comtesse.</p>
<p>Votre respectable et excellente qualit est couche duement dans le Contrat, ainsi que celle de votre serviteur.</p>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="ADMS-06-12-02-pb-0263">[263]</span>
<p>Enfin, nous avons une Maison Amricaine  La Haie noble, et telle quil convient  la dignit du Reprsentant des E.U., et je vous ferai voir  loisir, Monsieur, quavec le plaisir de la proprit, vous avez celui dhabiter pour une rente trs modre.</p>
<p>Je me rjouis de lclat que cette affaire fera certainement ici ds aujourdhui. Made. la Comtesse de Wickrad (Vendeur) ma charg de ses complimens pour V.E., et de vous dire, que le regret de sortir de sa maison, et dy perdre 2000 dachat et 2000 de rparation, a t adouci, lorsque je lui ai dit le nom de lAcheteur; ce que je nai fait que lors de la confection du Contrat: et quen bonne conscience, lorsque les Etats-Unis auront eu les succs quelle leur desire, ils la dedommageront.</p>
<p>Permettez une place ici  mes respects pour Mrs. Barclai et Thaxter, et soyez assur de celui, et de lattachement inviolable, avec lequel je suis pour toujours, Monsieur Votre trs-humble &amp; trs-obissant serviteur</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Dumas</p>
</div>
<div class="postscript">
<p>P.S. Je crois, et dautres amis aussi, quil convient de dire, que vous ne quittez le sejour dAmsterdam que pour la raison de votre sant: comme cela est vrai.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="PJA12d187" class="trans letter">

 <h2>C. W. F. Dumas to John Adams: A Translation</h2>
 
<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		  <td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		  <td class="salutationRight">The Hague, 23 February 1782</td>
		</tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>The house that your Excellency commissioned me to buy is yours as of last night. We presented a sales contract on your behalf before the notaries for fourteen thousand fifty-two and a half florins, 14,052.10s in Dutch currency, free of all fees, in return for which the seller will relinquish possession of the house on May 1st, just as you have seen it, free of all debts and other costs.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA12d187n1" id="PJA12d187n1-ptr">1</a> As a condition of the contract, I promised the sum of 8,000, payable upon receipt, to be made before March 1st. This is to pay off the existing mortgage. The remaining 6,052.10 will be paid next May 1st when the transfer takes place. In order to do this, today I withdrew a bill of exchange, payable to me, for 10,000 Dutch currency, endorsed by Mr. Moliere fils &amp; Co., against which he gave me two receipts payable to the bearer. One is for 8,000, which I will give to the notary, and the other is for 2,000, which I will leave at Mr. Molieres myself. This is in case I need any ready money for fees and anything else concerning the purchase, after you take account, sir, of the balance. As for the remaining 6,052.10, I will withdraw the funds from your account in order to pay it before May 1st, when the transfer takes place. My notary, as well as the one from the hotel de France, will send me a copy of the contract which I hope to be able to deliver to you myself, as soon as I have arranged for payment of the sale<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="ADMS-06-12-02-pb-0264">[264]</span> and fees. I must inform you, sir, that according to customary terms stated in the contract, the buyer assumes all responsibility of the propertys perils and risks as of yesterdays signing and therefore, for your peace of mind, you can insure it if you think it is necessary.</p>
<p>Moreover, I bargained up until the last moment and the seller had just enough time to stop a public auction. Because of this, I saved you, sir, 700 in fees more or less, in addition to the cost of a meal. Last Tuesday, there was an offer made for 13,000, and I have since then checked to make certain that I would not have had it for less than 14,000 at the public auction. I flatter myself that my behavior, in all respects, will meet with your approval and that you would be so kind, sir, as to send me a word that you are happy with me. Please receive my compliments on this acquisition, and my wishes that you enjoy it, in good health, and with many satisfactions, equal to the sincerity and heartfelt feelings of the one who presents them to you.</p>
<p>Immediately after signing the contract, I ran to the Htel de France (even though there was a ball) and asked La Vauguyons secretary to inform his Excellency of the sale. I was told that this morning, the Duke of Brunswicks courier went to our residence to inquire about the transaction with the countess.</p>
<p>Your respectable and excellent character is duly inserted in the contract, as well as that of your servant.</p>
<p>Finally we have an American residence at The Hague, noble and suitable for the dignity of an American representative. I will show it to you, at leisure, sir, and with the pleasure of ownership, you will inhabit it at a very moderate outlay of funds.</p>
<p>I rejoice at the noise this business will certainly make from now on. Madame Countess Wickrad (the seller) sends you her compliments and asked me to tell you that the hardships of leaving her house, losing 2,000 in the sale and another 2000 in repairs, were softened when I told her the name of the buyer. This I did not do until the contract was prepared, and in good conscience I told her that she would be compensated as soon as the United States had the successes that she desired for them.</p>
<p>Allow me to add here my respects for Mr. Barclay and Mr. Thaxter and be assured of my respect and inviolable attachment, with which I remain, sir, your very humble and very obedient servant</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Dumas</p>
</div>
<div class="postscript">
<p>P.S. I believe, as well as others do, that it would be best to say that you are leaving Amsterdam for health reasons. This way it is true.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
